%I A397520 #19 Jul 09 2026 07:58:24
%S A397520 0,1,2,3,17,18,32,34,4,6,38,36,66,64,8,9,16,19,128,130,65,96,7,68,40,
%T A397520 512,67,1024,11,33,256,10,129,80,26,257,82,35,259,50,513,272,24,132,
%U A397520 70,516,52,288,5,69,160,273,274,162,20,514,48,275,289,49,515,292,544
%N A397520 Lexicographically earliest infinite sequence of distinct nonnegative integers such that each 1-bit in the binary plot of the sequence is a knight's move apart from one, and only one, other 1-bit.
%C A397520 A variation of A396694: in the present sequence the 1-bits must be a knight's move apart from just one other 1-bit.
%C A397520 It is conjectured that all nonnegative numbers appear.
%C A397520 Note that to ensure the sequence is infinite numerous conditions must be met to ensure that no term violates the restriction that each 1-bit must be matched with one, and only one, other 1-bit. See the examples below.
%C A397520 The sequence cannot contain the number 341 (a 1-bit matching its central 1-bit necessarily matches another of its 1-bits). - _Rémy Sigrist_, Jul 09 2026
%C A397520 More generally, the sequence cannot contain any of 32*k + {21,23,29,31} because it is impossible to match the rightmost 1. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Jul 09 2026
%H A397520 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="/A397520/b397520.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..1000</a> (terms 0..240 from Scott R. Shannon)
%H A397520 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a397/A397520.java">Java program</a> (github)
%e A397520 The terms, with their binary values, begin:
%e A397520   n   a(n)   A007088(a(n))
%e A397520   --  ----  --------------
%e A397520    0     0               0
%e A397520    1     1               1
%e A397520    2     2              10
%e A397520    3     3              11
%e A397520    4    17           10001
%e A397520    5    18           10010
%e A397520    6    32          100000
%e A397520    7    34          100010
%e A397520    8     4             100
%e A397520    9     6             110
%e A397520   10    38          100110
%e A397520   11    36          100100
%e A397520   12    66         1000010
%e A397520   13    64         1000000
%e A397520   14     8            1000
%e A397520   15     9            1001
%e A397520   16    16           10000
%e A397520   17    19           10011
%e A397520   18   128        10000000
%e A397520   19   130        10000010
%e A397520   20    65         1000001
%e A397520 .
%e A397520 a(4) = 17 = 10001_2 as this term must be greater than 3, have a 1-bit in the lowest order bit to satisfy the 1-bit in a(2) = 2, while not containing a 1-bit in either the third or fourth lowest order bit.
%e A397520 a(5) = 18 = 10010_2 as this term must be greater than 3, have a 1-bit in the second-lowest order bit to satisfy the lowest order 1-bit in a(3) = 3, while not containing a 1-bit in its third lowest order bit. Note that the highest order 1 bit in a(4) = 17 is not yet satisfied which implies the 4th or 6th bit in a(6) must be a 1-bit. That excludes a(5) = 10 = 1010_2 as the 1's in its 2nd and 4th bits would match the required 1 bit in either the 4th or 6th bit of a(6), but that is not allowed as that 1-bit will already match the high order 1-bit in a(4) = 17.
%Y A397520 Cf. A396694, A394166, A397519, A007088, A396836, A109812.
